				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Most Useful Bard AA Abilities<a name="45975"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 14 04 5:35 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>SCF is nice to have, as bards have the reported lowest melee dps of all melees. Toss in a life tap aug and it's instant self healing of inconsequential damage.  There have been many groups where the only healing I've gotten were from life tap aug processes and Marr.  The comical, amusing side of this is that if you do process a crital hit using a life tap aug you also in essence succeed in doing a critical heal.
<br />

<br />
Run 5 is important from a standpoint of the pulling bard.  While some mobs outrun it, others do not.  A pulling bard is required to pull the mobs to the group, whether that is a raid setting or exp setting.  So this is kind of a no brainer for a puller, at least it was to me.
<br />

<br />
The one suggestion I would offer is to make The Big Three The Big Four.  While some bards have steered away from Boastful Bellows, most have not.  It adds dmg to all categories listed, with the possible exception of PvP.  Melee bards can use it for added melee dps (hey, every little bit helps).  Pullers use it as a pulling/positioning tool.  It would also remove it from the Puller's list, as being last well below Combat Fury wasn't in my mind a proper place for it regarding pullers.  Of course since most bards tend to wait until they are 65th to do most aa work I'd put it a lot higher in the list.  For those that never bought into 65&gt;all bs I could see it being lower on the list.
<br />

<br />
In addition, you should add Sinister Strike, for the same reason a several other aas.  It helps add additional dps.
<br />

<br />
Polara Magami</span></td>
